segments.text: and the overall thing have a good advanced program for a major where there would be some busting back and forth between the institutions.
This was the idea, to try to strengthen these colleges by any way that we could.
And I tried to set up these consortia in Little Rock, where there were three institutions, in Texas, where there were
six institutions scattered over a larger area in Memphis, in northern Mississippi, in Alabama.
Those are the main ones that seem to respond to the idea.
The Ford Foundation had promised support for any that was ready to move on.
I saw the greatest promise
originally in Little Rock, where all three institutions were right together.
They were a few miles apart.
I ran into the Methodist Church, the major institution in Little Rock, Philander Smith, a Methodist institution.
The Methodist Church was not willing
surrender its autonomy in this situation.

We had this back and forth and I could understand their feeling there because you see what we were trying to do in Little Rock was to sort of impose a university structure on the three things which of course would be controlled by the blacks.
found out the extent to which the land of Smith was controlled by whites.
That was one thing.

And, in fact, they had even asked me to come into Little Rocks, into Little Rocks, where I knew, I knew the sources of, knew where the money was in Arkansas, and I was in consultation with Rockefeller.
He was the governor of the state at that time.
Of course, his foundation had gone.
and developed many programs, or has since.
Incidentally, my nephew is president of that foundation in Arkansas, Tom McCrae.
But I was hopeful that that would be the one to get it started.
And they had asked me, at least administratively, to set this thing up.
Well, it didn't work.
I can't blame the Methodist Church.
No, it was just that the opposition to it came more from the Methodists than from Philander Smith, because that was the strongest of the institutions.
It had most to lose, I think, by a program of cooperation like this.
So the one that really emerged more and more
with a less binding and a more flexible kind of organization, particularly because the institution was separated, was in Texas.
And I, oh, as I look back on it, there are many things that I wish I had done, but it was not obvious at that point that Texas was going to be the one, or just how the structure should be set up.
The thing I was trying to do in the first meeting that I organized and called in Texas for this purpose was to involve the major universities in the structure, too.
For instance, the first meeting we had was at SMU in Dallas, and all of the black college presidents and the representative board members from each of them, and also
presidents of the predominantly white institutions.
Now, at that time, it was an interim president, I think it was Rogers, he was here in journalism, he was acting as interim president at North Texas.
He was involved, the president of SMU was there, the president of the chancellor of TCU, and so forth.
And what we worked out at that point,
was a structure which had a board of trustees.
It would be autonomous, but it would have representatives, equal, equal representatives with major universities in the area.
Obviously, the center would have to be Dallas because of the institutions.
These black colleges are all in the North Texas area?
Well, they go down as one in Dallas, one in Waco, one in Austin.
one in Marshall in East Texas, one in Tyler, one in Great Sandy, which is near Tyler, Jarvis Christian College, which is closer related to TCU there.
So there were six of them.
I could go either east on the interstate or south on the interstate from Dallas.
So Dallas was the central place for it.
So while I was gone at one point, the thing was actually organized.
And some power structure thing was set up which placed the power in the hands of the six black college presidents.
And that alienated some of the predominantly white university because, see, these were the institutions that had the resources.
The North Texas group was eager and enthusiastic about it and were willing to, without pay, to turn loose some of their staff and professors to work in these various programs and so forth.
And it, well,
Actually, it was the board, but there was an executive committee of the board consisting of the black college presidents.
And then a little later, there was a long history here of development of this thing.
I was simultaneously trying to develop others.
But this is the one that really emerged.
And the presidents were ready to move.
The Ford Foundation was right there, ready to back it.
And they were going to town.
And since I had been involved in the middle of this, and I'd been on the staff of the National Council of Churches for eight years, we had had New York.
And it would have meant a lot to us to be able to come back to Texas, and particularly to Denton.
So we figured, okay, we can live in Denton, and I can commute to Dallas, set up the office in Dallas, which we did an exchange party, which was close by and wasn't too bad commuting.

So we did that, and another white man who had been involved in the organization, he was the business manager type, the business manager at Austin College, came in as vice president, I was president, and then we soon were able to get a fundraising man, a black, terrific young fellow, who is now with the United Negro College Fund.
All of this publicity you see for UNCF, he's the one who organizes it and puts on the, what do they call them, the extravaganzas and this kind of thing.
But UNCF, that's United Negro College Fund.
We were related to them initially, but we were not dominated by them.
We had a separate structure here.
Well, this
had quite a history for a while here.
I was with this group for four years.
During that four years, the four colleges that were not accredited in that group were accredited.
We were able to bring in millions of dollars in support.
We were able to get programs from HUW, the federal programs
Well, we were just turning out proposals.
This was my real role, to write proposals and then to try to get them accepted either by foundations or by HEW or in some cases individuals who were interested in this whole thing.
And sometimes the greatest problem was getting them accepted on black colleges.
But more and more, as we were able to bring in funds, we were encroaching upon the autonomy of black institutions.
Same thing we had run into with Methodist Church in Little Auburn.
We were running into the CME Church, Christian Methodist Episcopal Church.

the AME Church, the AME Zion, African Methodist Episcopal, and African Methodist Episcopal Zion, so these are all separate Methodist denominations, as well as the American Baptist Convention, which was Bishop College in Texas.
Autonomy is a very difficult thing to surrender, even a slight area of autonomy in planning for six institutions at the same time, in developing programs.
Here was a good example of this.
We had a grant from HUW.
Oh, I think we had about $500,000 or $600,000 to develop a strong
business program for the six institutions, not just secretarial science.
They all could do that.
But really to have a good business major in every one of these, because obviously one of the areas that needed to be worked on in the black community was to have business school graduates.
I mean, people who could really organize and structure businesses in the black community or otherwise.
Well, I was working with people at North Texas on this one.
John Carroll, he is retired from the School of Business.
He was acting dean for a while.
He was a good friend.
Well, I got to know him at that time through Brock, Horace Brock here.
He was a good friend.
But at any rate, John Carroll was going to organize this thing.
He was given leave of absence in North Texas for a full year to work full time on it.
He was going to be able to get some high level faculty people at North Texas and at SMU and TCU to work specifically on some of these programs.
And it was, I think,
a Bachelor of Business Administration, it wasn't really called that in all of these, but to develop that kind of program.
Only one of the students had anything resembling that.
So, this was an all-out effort.
Well, we got the grant, we got the personnel, we were all gung-ho and ready to go.
Then we had a meeting, I guess this was
No, it was in Austin.
And John Carroll was there, he presented his plans, and so forth.
And my presidents, through the funding, said we will use these funds to apportion them to each individual institution.
except for a total of four appearances.
And we will not have this break.
And I had to go back and tell John Carroll that he was fired before he could get to work.
Boy, that hurt.
I could understand their position.
Each one of these presidents was fighting the budget battle.
They all had deficits.
They had to scrounge for every dollar they could get.

So the idea was we could maintain the appearance of this program by apparently channeling these grants to the business administration or the business departments of each one of these schools, and then having a small program, retaining Dr. Carroll, if he would work on this basis,

have some training sessions and so forth, and use some of these high-level faculty people at the universities and so forth, really more for the benefit of the faculty than for the students, and to try to enroll some of the faculty in some of the graduate programs in North Texas.
Well, this was disheartening because it was a real solid program that was worked out.
I guess that was the beginning of the end, as far as I was concerned, because they were so preoccupied.
And this was by necessity.
I understood this.
So preoccupied with making the budgets and the deficits.
It was impossible, really, to get beyond that.

Well, at the same time, we, with the young black man, Melvin Shaw, who was vice president for development and stuff, we had raised, in matching grants, Ford Foundation would match funds we could raise in Texas.
A very ambitious structure.
We had visions and had commitments of six million dollars to form a university structure for these six institutions.
It was pretty far out.
It was trying to move too far, too fast.

visited several schools, particularly in California, to try to learn as much about this kind of overall structure at the University of the Pacific, which is more or less on the Oxford England basis of having small autonomous colleges.
But still, there's a university structure that is overall
While there's autonomy in undergraduate education and so forth, the university structure would deal with the cooperative things between them.
Also, the University of California Center.
Is that the one that you helped?
Yes.
I'd been a consultant in establishing the religious program there, which .
But at any rate, this was based on small, autonomous colleges as well.
And so I visited both of those to see if we could find some structural means by which we could overcome this concern with loss of autonomy in these institutions.
And we simply were not able to do it.
I guess I went too far in trying to go too fast.
I lost the confidence of the black presidents, and I miss those nuances that I should have been listening for.
I don't know, maybe a white man can never get those, but it all ended very unhappily in that
Here we were ready in the structure of our little organization with three executive staff people, about a half dozen secretaries and so forth.
We were just an office and of course all the everything that we did was related to the college.
But we insisted that we could raise the funds but only
on the basis of maintaining the control of the funds and the universal structure, and working from that basis.
Because the foundations and HEW also were simply not willing.
There had already been a number of incidents.
Of course, the structure and the planning of a traditional black college is very different,
auditive accounts and so forth that we are accustomed to predominantly quite.
It wasn't a question of dishonesty as much as it was a question of power within the structure of the black church, within the structure of the black colleges.
So while we were working with the business administration, with the business departments of the colleges, trying to get competent,
business managers in the college, vice presidents for business or administration or something like that.
We had accomplished a good bit, and on the basis of some of the changes made, you see, there had been grants both to the individual colleges and other ones.
Well, during all of this time,
Bishop College was, of course, this was the major institution of these six.
It was the strongest, best financed, the best campus, newest buildings.
And it was the one that was pursuing its own program with the Ford Foundation to strengthen it.
Well, at the same time, we had this program worked out with the Ford Foundation commitment to go ahead with it if we could match bucks within the state of Texas.
We were working with the Brown Foundation, the Moody Foundation, the Sid Richardson Foundation, and this young fellow we had, Melvin Shaw, was really doing the job.
because he was bearding these people constantly.
And I would turn out, churn out the proposals.
Some of them, I think, were more for appearances than anything else.
But we were in a hurry.
I mean, we had to do something.
We knew the time was limited.
I'd been here nearly four years, and as I pointed out, something people didn't think was funny.
about how much tenure does a white president of a consortium of black colleges have.
I figured I would have 40 years before leadership could be turned over to a bunch of blacks.
I guess I was a necessary entree into the white community initially, but of course blacks by this time had full entree into
In fact, they were the favorite spokesmen for one of the colleges, two foundations, and even the staff at HEW about this time that dealt with these things was black.
A very lovely lady who had been president of Bennett College was the head of the section at HEW that dealt with that college.
sure shipped a lot of proposals her way.
But the point came where they simply were not willing to surrender this autonomy.
And there was a very specific rivalry here as far as Bishop College was concerned.
They were pursuing the same funds as Bishop College.
We had a severance of ways here.
In a sense, I was fired.
In a sense, I was unwilling to continue on the basis of what seemed to me to be misappropriation of funds.
You see, it was my name, and my integrity, and the integrity of the structure.
that would raise these funds, and then once they got them, they could be used for other purposes.
And legally, this was, I mean, I was getting into difficulty here, too, because I couldn't control the funds.
And this was a great tragedy.
It was a personal tragedy for me, even as much as the Hampton Sydney experience, because here was the other side of it.
And it turned out to be a tragic experience for the colleges as well, because three of these presidents were subsequently indicted.
I didn't, I stayed out of it from that point, once I was out of it.
I don't know, I guess there were some ways that I could have

I could have called it on this, but after all, I've been working for five years with the National Council in Texas to try to do something for these colleagues, to put them in the mainstream, help them come to the mainstream.
I think we accomplished some things, but we failed.
most critical and important to us.
Since that time, of course, Mission College has fallen into new lanes, and this was the strongest.
Probably the strongest remaining one was Houston Tillotson in Austin, because of the strong president they had through the years, John McKeith.
Jarvis Christian College
which is related to TCU, which is sort of a subsidiary of a white college.
Never has been in all kinds of black institutions.
They've trained a lot of black leaders, I think.
They've had two presidents.
And then Wiley College in Marshall.

president who was there when I was there when I was well he was he was the chairman of the board actually he left under some cloud and then the man who came in was indicted who really had nothing to do with it but he was carrying around policies
It's just a different world, and this is one thing I think both the courts and otherwise have to recognize about these institutions.
They have operated as arms of the black church, and the black church functions in a sort of a power way.
But I don't think any or many, certainly not many, of these people have ever feathered their own nests.
I think they've been honest and responsible in these terms.
But how they use funds and whether it is subject to an audit by Pete Martin and Mitchell or these big accounting firms,

We were trying to get their books in order so that they could be straightened out in this way, and what was basically an honest operation be put on the books so that it could be demonstrated to be by the white man's standards.
White man's way of doing things was by audits.
Black man's way of doing things was by
personalities, relationships, power structures within the church.
So they've had to conform, you see, to get money from any point of service and really to exist legally.
And it's been a difficult time.
I think the black colleges since that time, they had a renaissance.
They were able to
Not just the ones that we worked with particularly, but because of the federal programs and others.
For a while, they were able to move right along.
But inevitably, integration was taking place in higher education.
And again, these schools
I have become more remedial institutions.
There's still a real role for them, I'm sure.
And they graduate, and there are many people still.
And basically, they're still accredited by the Southern Association.
But there are problems.
And there are problems that can be alleviated fondly over a very close relationship with other higher education institutions.
So they're still acting at the community college level, really?
Yeah, they're four-year institutions.
But of course, when you consider the fact that a great many of the students are there, the whole first two years have to be remedial programs.
while the more select of those came from close to Falkland, Texas and other integrated institutions.
Of course, the public schools are largely integrated now, but when you get a school system like Dallas's, where some of the schools are primarily black student bodies, then you have, well,
There's still remedial training that needs to be done to do what kind of college it's at.
Of course, this happens in white schools, too.
I mean, for instance, gym.
He did pretty well in high school, played in the Honor Society and so forth, but he had to learn to read when he got to Davidson.
I mean, he had to take the speed reading course, which was kind of a remedial reading.
But Jim had never read for fun.
This was a thing.
Most of us who came along in the last generation, for entertainment we would read.

it's not so so much true for this this generation of students and uh read rapidly well this is the kind of thing that has to be done in our educational system throughout and it's just magnified several times those colleges as a whole just i've never been able to get that
broad sense of purpose that you all were trying to bring in just because they were getting so caught up in the, as you say, the deficits and trying to deal with the different cultures.
Right.
Well, this is the thing that we had to fight and deal with and where we lost the fight.
I guess that's why I focus upon that because this was the point of our defeat.
Their preoccupation
with surviving.
This is not only with the presidents and the administrators of the college, but with the churches that they are responsible to or related to.
This is their institution still.
And this is, well, there's just no way they can divorce themselves from it in terms of control.
in terms of autonomy, even if it's impossible to have adequate educational programs on that basis.
Because you see, the point was reached, and this was the real point where the government programs and the foundation programs were no longer, as it's often been expressed
pouring money down the rabbit hole.
If they couldn't see the specific results of the money that they gave, that was all they could do.
And if they could see it in terms of programs, and graduates, and fields, which were important for the improvement of the black situation, educationally in other words,
And the foundations were turning off.
And of course, the whole federal program now was the Reagan administration.
They reversed the Civil Rights Revolution in four years.
But any rate, it was the defeat of everything that was important to me, at least.
Important to a lot of people.
That's another story, I guess.
But the black, it's hard to kill an institution.
It's just that they're not progressive.
They've become largely remedial institutions with more and more
don't seem to be able to be solid.
They've turned inward, rather than outward.
Of course, what we would hope to realize, they can turn outward in terms of support, in terms of a radical education.
North Texas was the only state institution that was involved in that, concerning with the University of Texas or any other school?
Yes.
Now, others were involved primarily with the institutions, the local institutions.
For instance, University of Texas never did.
I never did get much response from them, but they have had programs with Houston Public Schools.
And Baylor with Paul Quinn, this is, never has been, much has never been involved.
But Paul Quinn is a Baptist school?
No, it's a Methodist school.
Oh, it's a Methodist school.
Now Baylor was more sympathetic toward, toward the College of Dallas, Bishop, because it's Baptist.
Nothing really practical, incidental, locally, in some cases.
But North Texas was the primary one, I think.
It's because some of us were involved here, the people that I knew here, who were interested and were able to get into Woodlands.
North Texas was in on the ground floor.
Austin College was real interesting because they were not a university.
But their president was very much involved in things.
He was very disciplined with the things.
But the way they did in East Texas, in Commerce, was they were setting up programs both with Wiley College and with Texas College.
Was that leadership base working in the school strong?
Were they from the South, or were they
from the North, like as you're educated in Princeton, plus your background.
That's what I meant with the other.
You're speaking of the whites or the blacks?
The people that were involved at North Texas, the people that were involved.
I think both, both.
For instance, the people that I was able to enlist in North Texas had primarily a Texas background, Southern background, East Texas, North Texas.
But, of course, they were educating institutions all over the country.
No, there's never been any regional bias here.
Of course, in the South, back in the old days, the more progressive elements were trying to do things about black education for a long time, and some of the strong leadership in this movement
has come from whites in the South.
And a lot of the people who moved to these black campuses, for instance, in Miles College in Birmingham, an outstanding place, I forget his name, moved down from Yale,
and set up a program in, well, this was one of the media programs, and so forth.
And there was a lot of publicity about this, but it was a genuine thing that he did.
He moved down there and stayed until his retirement.
And there have been a lot of instances of this kind of thing, not as well as public instances of it.
people from the major institutions have felt enough call and enough responsibility to get involved and to move onto these campuses to do the job that he's doing.
Did you have any interaction with Reverend Price from Lexington, Virginia?
I had read an article about that.
He was in the Presbyterian Church, and I had read
something about him talking at the General Assembly of the Southern Presbyterian Church, and he went out on a limb with that, and I think it was like May 28.
Nice.
Yeah, you're talking about a missionary from China.
Yeah, he was a moderator, had been moderator of the General Assembly.
Right, right.
He was, yes, he was very much involved in the early
Did he work with your wife's family there when you were in China?
Yes, yes they had in China.
They knew he was primarily in Shanghai and administrative roles in China and then he was there even after the communists came in.
didn't know which price you were talking about.
Yes, he was very much in the picture then and was certainly a leader in any kind of progressive or liberal ideas.
He was one of the leaders in the church as far as integration and
of the two branches of the church, and I guess it was probably that 54th General Assembly, wasn't it, where he was so much ahead of us?
Well, this is the one that I attended, and what came out of that meeting was a very strong
Yeah.
Were those missionaries, the missionaries that came back a strong force in trying to...
I think by and large they were.
Some of them were very conservative theologically, and unfortunately this
came as a sort of a conservative-liberal issue.
Of course, conservative in the South means conservative in social questions.
There are two different questions entirely.
Theological conservatism and liberalism, and social liberalism and conservatism.
Of course, more recently, those things have become so polarized
liberal as a liberal and a conservative as a conservative in the church or anywhere else without regard to some of the nuances in the situation.
But the missionaries, by and large, did support integration.
They did support the reunion of the two churches.
Of course, they had worked in China or everywhere else with Presbyterians of the other stripe.
Did you work at all with Russ College of Mississippi, Holly Springs, Mississippi?
Yeah.
That was where my father went down from here in Cato State to do an exchange program with their campus ministers.
Yeah.
And he's mentioned Northern Mississippi.
What was the date of that?
I was, my mother was pregnant at that time.
I think it was the spring of 1963.

Well, I had probably visited there, let's see, it was about a year or so before, and we were talking about, let's see, there are two colleges in Holly Springs, and then there are three in Memphis, which is not too far away.
Right.
And then there were two near Jackson.
That scattering, we didn't pursue too far.
That kind of separation.
But we talked to the people there.
Of course, they were eager to get in on something.
But, yes, I remember how they spread this very well.
I just spent, I think, a couple of days there.
We talked about a lot of things.
But that must have been about a year or more ago.
I've been browsing through some picture books.
Now, you were living there.
Well, my...
My dad was the campus minister of the Wesley Foundation up in Mankato.
And they came down to spend some time with my students.
Well, were you bored then?
No, I was just getting ready to work.
A few months ago.
Right, 63, 63.
Yeah, that's Jim's birthday.
A year or two.
Yeah.
Yeah, your wife would say she was thinking Jim was 23 the other day.
She lost it.
Yeah.
Easy to lose a year.
She probably could grow up real fast.
Yeah, well, you know, it's hard to...
sort of gauge time like that, from this perspective, because it's been a while.
Well, I appreciate it very much.
It's time to talk.
It's a privilege for me to rehash some of his old history.
It's been a lot of byways and
I suppose there's no, you do something like this with a strong moral feeling, but there are always compromises.
There's nothing black and white about it in terms of morality.
A lot of the things I think I would have done differently.
I don't know, maybe it had to be confrontation.
the confrontation of people like Martin Luther King.
Of course, he was always insistent that it was non-violence and so forth, and it was to a certain extent, but it was confrontation.
It was antagonism.
And some of the things I deliberately, well, let me go on and mention a couple of other things.
Some of the things I deliberately didn't
participating because I wasn't really with him.
One of them was the Selma March in which Martin Luther King was present.
Of course, they were deliberately trying to bring on violence for the reaction that it would get for the cause of
equality and freedom and what have you, knowing that the rednecks in Alabama would oppose it with violence and so forth.
But one perspective that I got on this, I have some cousins in Selma, Alabama.
They are part of the medical community there.
And they were considered the medical group
there, the group of doctors and hospital, were very concerned.
They thought there was going to be even more violence than there was because all of the rednecks in the surrounding country had been harming themselves and making all kinds of outlandish statements.
And when it looked as if it was inevitable, this march to Montgomery from Selma,

uh what the local and this this is on the records of the medical association they went to the organizers of this and said look there's going to be violence we are here to serve those who need help we're not going to take any position on what you're doing
As far as that concerns, our only purpose is to provide medical help, because we think it's important.
And be free to come to us, to the hospital, anything that happens, because we are determined to minimize this as much as possible and help in every way that we can.
Well, they were turned down because of a fight.
Because they were fearful, I think, that there would be some kind of betrayal.
They really trusted them.
Well, there were two people killed there.
One was Reed, James Reed, I think.
He was a graduate of Princeton Seminary.
